title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W model 1 2nd issue. and H&R Victor .22short.  WTB O/U 12g
postcontent:
Hi folks, I'm selling a highly collectable S&W model 1, 2nd issue, made between 1860 & 1868. These are few and rarely found in good condition. This one is good enough it can actually be fired but of course this is a valuable collector piece and is respectfully retired. The timing is good, springs are still strong, teeth on the cylinder are in great shape, etc.. As you can see, the nickle plating on the cylinder is mostly gone but for maybe 20%. The rest of the gun retains I'd say around 90% of the nickel finish and definitely shows it’s age but is obviously all original. Overall this is a great piece for the collection. The grips are in great shape as well. I tried to get some good pictures here and of course feel free to ask questions. Being an antique, this does not require an FFL.  Value is $400.

Also is a Victor D/S action .22 revolver and it's also in great condition and shoots fine.  The frame is finished in Titanium Dura Coat and it comes with a holster, 80 rounds of ammo and a hard case.  The Victor with accessories is valued at $200.

I'll pay cash and/or trade for a suitable shotgun to use at the trap range.  My first choice is a 12gauge over/under but will consider others. 
I also have several types of ammo that I'm willing to barter with as well, and I do mean at normal store prices, not inflated, low-life, scumbag, scalper prices.

title: For Sale:  Gunsmith Build Colt series MK IV series 80 upper on a size 70
postcontent: The slide is a Colt Officers ACP with a 3&1/2 inch barrel. Because the slide is so short there was no room for the bushing to go when the slide went back. Therefore a larger bushing was made that slips over the barrel lugs during recoil, and the barrel diameter was belled to match. Another reason is with the shorter slide and barrel, the barrel angle would be too steep for the slide to function properly during recoil. A straight barrel would wedge the slide back during recoil. The shape of the bell keeps the barrel angled properly for slide function, and then realigns the barrel to the slide as the slide closes; there is a considerable amount of torque in a barrel and this is more evident in a short barrel. This barrel is beautifully bright. The ejection port is opened way out for trouble free ejection. Why put a series 80 on a frame size 70. A challenge I would say. A single action with polished receiver and trigger job. The grip is surrounded with a molded rubber grip sides and front. Rubber checkered easy grip under the grip safety. This is built on a series 70 size Federal Ordinance Frame.( mostly known for the VietNam era M-14) The safety is left side with a high grip safety. It took alot of time and work to make this series 80 fit atop a basically series 70. But it works and it works well. Easily concealed, plenty of knock down power.
